How HashMap works in Java?
ANSWER:  HashMap in Java works on hashing principle.

What is ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException in Java? When it occurs?
ANSWER:  ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException is thrown to indicate that we are trying to access an Array element with an illegal index.
This exception is thrown when the index is either negative or greater than or equal to the size of the Array.


What are the different ways of copying an Array into another Array?
ANSWER:  Arrays.copyOf() method to copy an Array in Java.

What is the difference between an Array and a LinkedList?
ANSWER:  The major difference between Array and Linked list regards to their structure. Arrays are index based Data Structures where each element is associated with an index. On the other hand, Linked list relies on references where each node consists of the data and the references to the previous and next element.

What is DFS and BFS?
ANSWER:  The breadth first search (BFS) and the depth first search (DFS) are the two algorithms used for traversing and searching a node in a graph.
BFS stands for Breadth First Search is a vertex based technique for finding the shortest path in a graph. It uses a Queue data structure which follows first in first out. In BFS, one vertex is selected at a time when it is visited and marked then its adjacent are visited and stored in the queue. It is slower than DFS.
DFS stands for Depth First Search is an edge based technique. It uses the Stack data structure, performs two stages, first visited vertices are pushed into stack and second if there are no vertices then visited vertices are popped.


What is Recursion?
ANSWER:  Recursion is a common method of simplifying a problem into subproblems of the same type. This is called divide and conquer technique.

What are linear and non linear Data Structures?
ANSWER:  The linear and non-linear Data Structures is the sub classification of the Data Structures which comes under the
Non-primitive Data Structures. The crucial difference between them is that the linear Data Structures arranges the data into a sequence and follow some sort of order. Whereas, the non-linear Data Structures does not organize the data in a sequential manner.

What is Big-(O)-notation?
ANSWER:  Big O specifically describes the worst-case scenario, and can be used to describe the execution time required or the space used (e.g. in memory or on disk) by an algorithm.
